LOCALITY: Tule Lake - DHL Singlewide 1 mile NW of Bloody Point
TRIP COMMENTS:
Modoc Plateau Trip Day 3
overcast, 55F at sunrise, north breeze. Clouds continued to build and move in from north. Packed up the campsite in the morning and headed into LABE where cleared vista to the north made it clear that we were in for rain as the morning progressed. Brief walk around the Catacombs area 06:50-07:20 before the rain set in at 07:20. Drove into Tulelake, stopping at Captain Jack's Stronghold restaurant for breakfast, but they were not open yet at 08:30, so we drove over to a flooded ag field that DHL knew about and found Wilson's Phalarope and Blue-winged Teal. Got breakfast 0940-1030, then headed to DHL's singlewide for showers and a break. Rain stopped, then over to Petroglyph Point to look for Prairie Falcon with no success, then past Tule Lake Sump 1B, back into LABE around 14:20, and took walk around Captain Jack's Stronghold, DHL giving an interpretive walk for Devii along the way. Headed to campground well for a quick dinner, then took a walk on the Three Sisters trail in the evening, finding a Pinyon Jay, then sat beside the E opening of Post Office Cave for about 45 minutes and then back to Modoc NF to camp, this time closer to Tionesta.

LOCALITY: Lake San Antonio--north end and/or Pleyto
TRIP COMMENTS: It was a mild-to-warm, clear day when we explored Lake San Antonio.  We first (for about 2/3 of this time and only 2 miles worth) explored the north side of the lake.  There were twelve large peninsulas, and each of them, plus the large lagoon at the southern tip, had at least 50 American Coots - hence our estimate of 700.  The best bird was a lone female Phainopepla around Road #8.  We were trying to pish up some Oak Titmice, which we were hearing, when the Phainopepla flew in and started eating berries.  The last hour or so of our time was spent looking for the extreme north end dam; we explored where the bridge crosses the San Antonio River, where we added the California Thrasher.  We also ennjoyed Pleyto Cemetery Road.

Conducting the Orange County Northeastern Christmas Bird Count, in Nancy Kenyon and Neal Anderson's area (Irvine Lake and the nearby Hick's/Blue Diamond Haul Road, along with portions of the private camps along the haul road). This was the first year (I believe) that I was finally able to get out of my old (area leader) assignments for the NE count (for like 20-25 years doing the O'Neill Regional Park and vicinity, then maybe 6 or 8 years being area leader of the Lemon/Cowan Heights area). COVERAGE: Besides doing the entire south and southeast shorelines of the lake, the west slope (a road that goes up to some old dwellings on the upper west slope), we also drove out the haul roads, out east of the lake, and then followed the road to the southeast, across Santiago Canyon Road, and then into the Lower Limestone Canyon. We birded the lower 1/2 mile of Limestone (just south of Santiago Can. Rd.  WEATHER: Mostly clear (except for a 30-40% cover of high thin clouds). Calm to 5mph breezes. About 35 (deg. F) at start!  Warming to a high 60s high. HABITATS:  Open water of the lake, but little to almost no marsh-type vegetation, except possibly for the northeastern corner, where Santiago Creek feeds into the lake, but we couldn't get over to that area. Also coastal sage scrub; mixed sage scrub/chaparral; some limited chaparral and coast live oak woodland on north-slope terrain at southeast and eastern edges of the lake; fairly small areas of riparian habitat that were connected to small tributaries to the lake on the southwestern and southeastern sides; and exotic plantings (lots of pines, some sycamore, eucalyptus, and Lombardy poplars and cottonwoods, etc., associated with the private camps on the east side). ----The following was taken directly from my birding notes for this date and location. ----Abbreviations:  IL = Irvine Lake;  HR = Haul Road.
SPECIES COMMENTS: Both were adult types. Together, soaring high over the lake, picked out by Neal. Circled overhead, or at least in view, for 15-20 minutes (when a raven occasionally was harassing one or the other). One definitely a nice adult, though the other seemed to have duskiness in the tail, especially the central rectrices. So possibly a subadult?  Irvine Lake staff told us they'd been seeing one Bald Eagle here for a while.

TRIP COMMENTS: I wanted to show Shantanu this eagle nest, so we drove up the road.  Because this is such a narrow road, requiring great concentration, I can''t really count the swallow flocks accurately.  We stopped near the nest, got out of the car, and looked around for awhile, adding species thus.  A bit cool and overcast at this point.

Michelle and I drove along Calaveras Road to add the Bald Eagle to the Big Day list.  We were delighted to find the Yellow-billed Magpie in the road!  The swallow numbers were impossible to count from a moving vehicle on a winding road (we nearly had an accident because of some hot-rod drivers, so we were tense).  Sunny and nice; the wind had not yet started
As it started to rain, we decided to go for the Bald Eagle nesting at the reservoir.  Can''t miss it!  Me and Gary Deghi.

Observations from around my yard and feeders. Partly cloudy, high 40''s, low 50''s. Mature bald eagle flew over yard, happened to have binocs and was able to confirm id.

Observations from bicycle ride to Clear Creek and back on highway 96. Partly cloudy, mid 40''s to mid 50''s. Flock of Lesser goldfinch feeding on alder catkins @ mouth of Elk Creek. Immature bald eagle, immature red-tail hawk, binos on both.

Observations from bicycle ride to Clear Creek and back on highway 96. Partly cloudy, mid 50''s. Mature bald eagle was chased and harassed by mature golden eagle. Bald eagle broke branch in snag as it took off in a hurry to avoid attack. Good looks at both birds. Pee Wee calling in top of cottonwood at river bridge. Black-cap chickadees in several areas along ride, voice and visual id.

Observations from bicycle ride to Clear Creek and back on hiway 96. Sunny, few clouds, mid 40''s to mid 50''s. Mature golden eagle in same snag as before. Immature bald eagle (salt n pepper) just upstream of golden eagle. Northern Pygmy Owl perched in spike top doug fir at eye level. Wonderful views w/binocs. New species for me!

TRIP COMMENTS: Birds listed on auto tour route. Water cells deep and more suitable for diving ducks and grebes. Note lack of dabbler ducks. (The extensive areas and large waterfowl numbers made estimating numbers difficult).

Our first time here was an amazing trip around Lake Meiss.  We were stunned by the human emptiness, and the abundance of birds.  Lots of firsts for the year and for the state year.  Beautiful day - warm, sunny, but not oppressively hot.  The birds were active, despite our late start.  Me, Peggy and Shantanu.  We also saw a family of Beaver

LOCALITY: Tule Lake NWR--Auto Tour and Sump 1A

TRIP COMMENTS: Observations from a float on the Klamath River from Wingate Bar to Ferry Point.  Clear, high 80''s. I located a new bald eagle nest for the first time! The nest is directly across the river from Ferry Point access. At least one chick on nest, it was exercising its wings. Adult bald led me into the nest.  Very exciting!! Several active osprey nests on this stretch of river also.

Observations from a bicycle ride to Clear Creek and back on hiway 96. Fire in the canyon!  Backing fire along a couple of mile stretch, drift smoke and overall smoky conditions.  Hot when starting, high 90''s cooling to high 70''s by dusk. Mature eagle and immature eagle. Watched large black bear for several minutes. Also saw striped skunk and gray fox during the ride. Several hotshot crews were present also.
Observers: Ann and Bill Toneff--Historical records processed by R. Kenneth Ostermiller

I continued on to Lower Klamath NWR & Tule Lake. Lots of BLACK TERNS & a few FRANKLIN''S GULL cruised the water at Tule Lake; SNOWY EGRETS & COMMON YELLOWTHROATS were in the marsh area, and lots of ducks & babies everywhere else. White Lake was dry.

Observations from a Klamath River float from Chamber''s Flat to Wingate Bar. Clear, hot, 100 to high 90''s.--Vultures kettling @ mouth of Elk Creek. Immature Northern Harrier flew into willows @ Buzzard Creek.
Cool.  Native Birds field trip with Rich Stallcup.

Observations from bicycle ride from Happy Camp to Clear Creek and back on highway 96. Clear, cold, low to mid 30''s.--One salt-n-pepper juv bald eagle, two adults. Cedar waxwings feeding on madrone berries. Wrentit by voice.

LOCALITY: Klamath Basin NWR Complex--Visitor Center area
